Since for generations blacks have been afforded inadequate educational opportunities and have been culturally segregated from white society, it is no more surprising that their performance on \u8216\'3fintelligence\u8217\'3f tests is significantly different than whites\rquote  than it is that fewer blacks have high school diplomas. In one instance, for example, it was found that 58% Of whites could pass a battery of standardized tests, as compared with only 6% Of the blacks. Included among those tests were the Wonderlic and Bennett tests. Decision of EEOC, cited in CCH Empl.Prac.Guide P1209.25 (Dec. 2, 1966).
