The majority argues that congressional action some years after the passage of the 1964 Act supports the Company\rquote s position. This is not legislative history. Even if the import of the action were unequivocal it would not speak for the will of the 88th Congress which passed the statute.
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa200 \sb0 
The cited legislative deliberation was occasioned by a bill introduced in May 1968 to modify Title VII. See S. 3465, 90th Cong., 2d Sess. \u167\'3f 6(c) (1968). If adopted it would have amended \u167\'3f 703(h) to embody a job-related standard in express terms. However, the bill was not enacted. One can draw differing and inconsistent conclusions from these events. It could be argued, as the majority does, that the bill\rquote s proponents recognized that \u167\'3f 703(h) as it stands does not contemplate job-relation. It is equally possible that the bill ultimately did not pass because the amendment was thought to be unnecessary. The bill\rquote s adherents might also have thought that the new amendment would represent no change, but offered it to forestall employers, such as Duke Power, from construing \u167\'3f 703(h) incorrectly. The inferences to be drawn from the introduction of the bill and its death are at best ambiguous and inconclusive.
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa200 \sb0 
If one must look to subsequent events for elucidation, consideration might be given to the comment of a Senator who was intimately involved in the passage of \u167\'3f 703(h). Senator Humphrey has stated that in his view \u167\'3f 703(h) did not protect tests if they were \u8216\'3firrelevant to the actual job requirements.\u8217\'3f Letter to American Psychological Association, quoted in The Ind. Psychologist (Div. 14, Am. Psychological Ass\rquote n Newsletter), August, 1965, at 6, cited in Cooper and Sobel, 1653, n. 67.
\par 
}
}
}
}
