*426
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
 or passing of a standardized general intelligence test as a condition of employment in or transfer to jobs when (a) neither standard is shown to be significantly related to successful job performance, (b) both requirements operate to disqualify Negroes at a substantially higher rate than white applicants, and (c) the jobs in question formerly had been filled only by white employees as part of a longstanding practice of giving preference to whites.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00011971127025_ID0EX4AE_10}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00011971127025_ID0EX4AE_10}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00011971127025_10" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
1
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
Congress provided, in Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, for class actions for enforcement of provisions of the Act and this proceeding was brought by a group of incumbent Negro employees against Duke Power Company. All the petitioners are employed at the Company\rquote s Dan River Steam Station, a power generating facility located at Draper, North Carolina. At the time this action was instituted, the Company had 95 employees at the Dan River Station, 14 of whom were Negroes; 13 of these are petitioners here.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The District Court found that prior to July 2, 1965, the effective date of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_780_427_10}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_780_427_10}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*427
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Company openly discriminated on the basis of race in the hiring and assigning of employees at its Dan River plant. The plant was organized into five operating departments: (1) Labor, (2) Coal Handling, (3) Operations, (4) Maintenance, and (5) Laboratory and Test. Negroes were employed only in the Labor Department where the highest paying jobs paid less than the lowest paying jobs in the other four \u8216\'3foperating\u8217\'3f departments in which only whites were employed.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00021971127025_ID0EMBAG_10}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00021971127025_ID0EMBAG_10}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00021971127025_10" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
2
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
 Promotions were normally made within each department on the basis of job seniority. Transferees into a department usually began in the lowest position.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In 1955 the Company instituted a policy of requiring a high school education for initial assignment to any department except Labor, and for transfer from the Coal Handling to any \u8216\'3finside\u8217\'3f department (Operations, Maintenance, or Laboratory). When the Company abandoned its policy of restricting Negroes to the Labor Department in 1965, completion of high school also was made a prerequisite to transfer from Labor to any other department. From the time the high school requirement was instituted to the time of trial, however, white employees hired before the time of the high school education requirement continued to perform satisfactorily and achieve promotions in the \u8216\'3foperating\u8217\'3f 
}
