{\ri0 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa200 \sb0 
Senator Tower\rquote s original amendment provided in part that a test would be permissible \u8216\'3fif * * * in the case of any individual who is seeking employment with such employer, such test is designed to determine or predict whether such individual is suitable or trainable with respect to his employment in the particular business or enterprise involved * * *.\u8217\'3f 110 Cong.Rec. 13492. This language indicates that Senator Tower\rquote s aim was simply to make certain that job-related tests would be permitted. The opposition to the amendment was based on its loose wording which the proponents of Title VII feared would be susceptible of misinterpretation. The final amendment, which was acceptable to all sides, could hardly have required less of a job relation than the first.
\par 
}
}
}
}
